\begin_layout Section*
Q3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
After training,
 analyze the residual stream geometry.
 What structure is there?
 How does it relate to the belief geometries of the component processes?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We construct a non-ergodic dataset from 8 Mess3 instances with distinct parameter pairs
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha,x)$
\end_inset

 and train a small GPT-2 style transformer (3 layers,

\begin_inset Formula $d_{\text{model}}=64$
\end_inset

,
 context window 16) via next-token prediction.
 See Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:training-details"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for full training details.
 All residual stream visualizations in the main text use PCA,
 which is unsupervised and therefore a weaker ask: any structure visible in PCA must be among the dominant directions of variance,
 not a consequence of fitting to known labels.
 Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:supervised-appendix"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the same analyses using a supervised linear readout to ground-truth belief states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Residual stream geometry across layers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We extract residual stream activations at all sequence positions after each layer (embedding,
 layer 0,
 layer 1,
 layer 2) and project them to 2D via PCA (Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:embed_per_instance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Each column shows one Mess3 instance: each row shows one layer,
 with the embedding at the bottom and the deepest layer at the top.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the embedding layer,
 structure is minimal: activations reflect token identity more than latent state.
 In deeper layers,
 activations progressively organize into instance-specific geometries.
 For instances with strong emission signals (high
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 low
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

),
 the residual stream develops clear simplex-like structure consistent with the 2-simplex of belief states over 3 hidden states.
 For noisier instances,
 the geometry is more diffuse but still differentiable from other instances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is consistent with the prediction from Q2 that deeper layers should encode the belief state
\begin_inset Formula $P(\bm{s}_{t}|x_{1:t})$
\end_inset

,
 and that each instance's belief states live on a 2-simplex embedded in an orthogonal subspace of the residual stream.
\end_layout

