\begin_layout Subsection*
Instance separation over context position
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test whether the transformer progressively infers which instance it is in,
 we examine how residual stream representations separate across instances as a function of sequence position.
 We select two pairs: a
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 pair with similar parameters (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.79,x=0.11$
\end_inset

 vs
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.85,x=0.10$
\end_inset

) and an
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

easy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 pair with very different parameters (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.90,x=0.05$
\end_inset

 vs
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.60,x=0.50$
\end_inset

).
 We embed activations from each pair jointly and plot them at each position (Figures
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:separation_hard"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:separation_easy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At position 0,
 both pairs are fully overlapping: the model has seen only one token and cannot distinguish the underlying process.
 As context accumulates,
 the clusters progressively separate,
 particularly in deeper layers.
 As expected,
 the easy pair separates earlier and more cleanly than the hard pair.
 This confirms that the transformer uses context to perform Bayesian-like inference over the identity of the generating process.
\end_layout

