\begin_layout Subsection*
Flow fields conditioned on incoming evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To visualize how individual token observations update the residual stream,
 we compute flow fields: for each position
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 the velocity
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\bm{h}=\bm{h}_{t+1}-\bm{h}_{t}$
\end_inset

 in PCA space,
 conditioned on the incoming token
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t+1}\in\{0,1,2\}$
\end_inset

 (Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:flow"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Each column corresponds to one token value: each row to one layer.
 We chose this analysis because the theoretical framework in Q2 predicts that incoming evidence
\begin_inset Formula $\log P(x_{t}|\bm{s}_{t})$
\end_inset

 should act as a velocity in latent space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flow fields show that each token drives the representation in a characteristic direction,
 and these directions become more structured in deeper layers.
 This suggests the transformer implements approximate belief updates where each token pushes the latent representation toward the simplex vertex associated with that token's preferred hidden state.
\end_layout

