\begin_layout Subsection*
Proposals for further analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
1.
 Subspace orthogonality.

\series default
 Measure whether the subspaces used by different instances are orthogonal,
 following the vary-one analysis of Shai et al.
 The prediction is that each instance's belief state should live in an approximately orthogonal 2-dimensional subspace (since each Mess3 factor has
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}-1=2$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
2.
 Causal interventions.

\series default
 Perform activation patching to test whether the identified subspaces are causally relevant: projecting out an instance's subspace should impair prediction for that instance while leaving other instances unaffected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:training-details"

\end_inset

Appendix A: Training details
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We construct a non-ergodic dataset from 8 Mess3 instances with parameter pairs
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha,x)\in\{(0.60,0.15),(0.79,0.11),(0.60,0.50),(0.90,0.05),(0.40,0.30),(0.70,0.25),(0.85,0.10),(0.50,0.40)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each Mess3 instance is a 3-state HMM emitting tokens from
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1,2\}$
\end_inset

,
 parameterized by
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 (emission peakedness) and
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (hidden state mixing rate).
 We sample 10,000 sequences of length 16 per instance (80,000 total),
 where each sequence is generated entirely from one ergodic instance.
 The model sees only token sequences: no instance label is provided.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transformer has 3 layers,

\begin_inset Formula $d_{\text{model}}=64$
\end_inset

,

\begin_inset Formula $d_{\text{MLP}}=256$
\end_inset

,
 4 attention heads,
 and a context window of 16 (151k parameters).
 We train with Adam (
\begin_inset Formula $\text{lr}=3\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset

) for up to 200 epochs with early stopping: we fit a line to
\begin_inset Formula $\log(\text{epoch})$
\end_inset

 vs
\begin_inset Formula $\log(\text{loss})$
\end_inset

 over the last 20 epochs and stop when the slope exceeds
\begin_inset Formula $-0.005$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:loss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows per-instance loss curves.
 Instances with high
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and low
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (strong signal,
 slow mixing) converge to lower loss,
 while those with low
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 or high
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 approach the entropy floor
\begin_inset Formula $\log3\approx1.099$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

